title: For Sale:  Rocket - Czech Military PG-15 Rocket
postcontent:
Czech Military PG-15 Rocket. Inert collectible new in the wrapper. Base fins fold outward to help guide the Rocket. 34 1/2 " tall with Czech writing on sides. Late '70s era and weighs 7 lbs., 12 Oz’s. Removable base propellant charge. Great for the Man Room! Makes a fantastic collector's piece for the military enthusiast. 
This is the Training version of the SPG-9 Kopye 73mm Recoilless Gun Round. It was launched by the base charge which gave it a velocity up to 400 meters per second and imparted spin to the rocket by a series of offset holes. The second stage rocket motor kicked in beyond 20 meters propelling it at a speed of 700 meters per second until burnout. 
This item is a militeria curio and is permanently inert and filled with a non-removable epoxy filler. It has no harmful parts or substances and cannot be modified into any harmful device. It is sold for its history, collectability and as an interesting conversation piece.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 870 police magnum
postcontent: $250 without the extended mag tube Remington 870 police magnum 20" barrel Comes with a Nordic Components extended mag tube bringing it to 7+1, Original SOE 6 round shot card, and an Elzetta flashlight mount. Will include original mag spring, plug, and cap. Here is a list of differences between the Express model and the Police model • 870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list – ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection. • All Police shotguns are assembled in a “special build area” at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build LE and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift. • All parts that enter the “special build area” are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality. • Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function. • A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs. • A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds. • Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety. • The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks. • The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty. • The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing. • The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a “ball detent” system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade “synthetic magazine spring retainer” lock down as used on the Express system.. • Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
FERFRANS Muzzle Brake Concussion Reduction System

Description:

The FERFRANS CQB Modular Muzzle Brake System is a two part system consisting of the performance muzzle brake mount + CRD (Concussion Reduction Device) which features a built in quick attach/detach mechanism. 

The muzzle brake effectively mitigates felt recoil and muzzle movement and with the CRD attached does this while minimizing side blast/concussion and redirects sound to the front of the shooter. It is a two piece modular system that includes (1) very effective high performance muzzle brake and (2) a ported Concussion Reduction Device (CRD) that attaches to the muzzle brake using a quick detach mechanism. The CRD has strategically placed side ports that allow the muzzle brake to retain its compensator functionality as opposed to brake shields that cover the brake and negates its function. 

With the CRD attached, recoil feels like a slight, straight to the rear push (it's a softer recoil feel, not the typical sharp kick). It is, of course, a compromise between reducing side concussion versus minimizing felt recoil. We believe we have achieved an optimal balance of sufficient brake/ compensator functionality (muzzle leveling effect) and side concussion reduction. The CRD has a quick detach/attach mechanism to allow you to easily switch back to a full brake whenever you.

Mostly original WWII M1 manufactured by the National Armory at Springfield Massachusetts in June of 1943.
Non-import; NO import markings. CMP rifle purchased a few years ago from the original owner. 
Original barrel is dated 6-43. Type II lockbar rear sights. -12SA bolt. WWII SA gas cylinder and correct lock is SA WWII with the bevel. Lock screw is a later replacement as you would expect to find. Oprod is D35382 SA with relief cut. Stock is correct, can still see the EcMf Final Inspection Stamp, or "Cartouche" as most refer to it. Correct for this date of manufacture. Can still see the firing proof 'P' as well. Has a small hole near the bottom of the grip where a arms room tag or metal stock disc insert would have been, about the size of a nickel/quarter. Also has the serial number of another rifle imprinted in lower portion of butt, below the grip. Handguards have later metal. Buttplate is WWII SA. Trigger group is correct and appears original in finish to the parts as a whole. Milled trigger guard, early -1 SA, housing is -5 SA, hammer is C46008-2 SA, safety is marked SA.

Not too much work required to fill the tag/disc indent in the stock, steam and raise the previous serial number out, and obtain a few needed parts to make this a 100% correct WWII rifle worth $3500.00 to $4500.00, or leave as is and enjoy it as what it is, a survivor that had a few parts replaced along the way as upgrades were available.
